1. Introduction
Dataset 1: Texas Health Rankings
The ﬁrst data set was provided by the County Health Rankings & Roadmaps (CHR&R) program by
University of Wisconsin Population Health Institute. The dataset was retrieved from
https://www.countyhealthrankings.org/explore-health-rankings/texas/data-and-resources
(https://www.countyhealthrankings.org/explore-health-rankings/texas/data-and-resources) and covers
various diﬀerent health statistics, ranging from death and mortality (of both adults and infants), high school
graduates, drinking accidents, etc.
The dataset contains 256 rows, where the ﬁrst 2 rows are the column names and each other row in this
dataset representing info about a particular county in Texas. In this dataset, there are 162 columns. Since
the dataset originated from a Microsoft Excel sheet and was later converted to a CSV ﬁle, certain columns
were merged and then un-merged without a proper name. Excluding these columns with missing names,
there are 82 columns, which give a statistic to each County based on
Commute (Long commute - driving alone, …),
Housing (Driving alone to work, …),
Environmental Violations (Drinking water violations, Air pollution - particulate matter, …),
Crime, death, and injuries (Violent crime, Injury deaths, …),
and other Health Factors (Physical inactivity, Poor or fair health, Excessive drinking,…).
What intrigued us about this data set was the possibility of health disparities between counties in Texas,
and to see if perhaps wealthier counties had better health statuses than less-wealthy counties.
Dataset 2: Texas Commission on Environmental Quality
Our second dataset was provided by the Texas Commission on Environmental Quality. The dataset was
retrieved from https://data.texas.gov/dataset/Texas-Commission-on-Environmental-Quality-Notices-/mwzi-
gyw7 (https://data.texas.gov/dataset/Texas-Commission-on-Environmental-Quality-Notices-/mwzi-gyw7)
and covers investigations leading to a Notice of Violation (NOV).

The dataset contains 1.2 million rows, as it covers data from each county from 2011 to 2023. Each row in
this dataset represents a Notice of Violation. In this dataset, there are 25 columns, correlating to
Identiﬁcation (Customer Name, Investigation Number, Notice of Violation Date, …),
Location data (Mailing Address, County, Latitude, Longitude…),
and Violation Classiﬁcation (Rule Citation, Media, Violation Category…).
What is particularly interesting about this dataset is while it does contain a plethora of environmental
violations, there does not appear to be a grand number of classiﬁcations. For example, all of the
information on NOVs seem to fall under only 3 media: Water, Air, and Waste. Similarly, NOVs fall under only
3 Violation Categories: A, B, and C.
Dataset 3 : Texas State Expenditures
Our third dataset was provided by the Texas Comptroller of Public Accounts. The dataset was retrieved
from https://data.texas.gov/Government-and-Taxes/Texas-State-Expenditures-by-County-2018/f2iw-dtqt
(https://data.texas.gov/Government-and-Taxes/Texas-State-Expenditures-by-County-2018/f2iw-dtqt) and
documents the amounts of money allocated by the state of Texas to each county, as well as the
corresponding expenditure category.
The dataset contains 88,707 rows, with each row representing a distinct expenditure made. The dataset
contains 6 diﬀerent variables, which are both
Numerical (Fiscal Year, Agency Number, and Amount),
and Categorical (Agency Name, County, and Major Spending Category).
What intrigued us about this data set was to see the relationship between the amount and category of
money allocated. Furthermore, when investigating the top-ranked average salary group, we wondered if the
counties represented would be well-known, larger counties.

RQ 1: Air Violations and Air Pollution
The ﬁrst research question, that will be explored, is the relationship between the amount of air violations in
a given county (in the dataset TX_Envm ) and the average daily “ ” (in the dataset TX_Health ).
Knowing this, let’s create a joined dataset, RQ_1 , for this research question utilizing both TX_Envm and
TX_Health . However, we must keep some issues in mind:
1. Both datasets will be joined by county. However, TX_Health has the counties capitalized in
sentence case, while TX_Envm has the counties in upper case. This must be adjusted to allow for a
proper join.
2. The TX_Health dataset only has information from 2017, while TX_Envm contains data from many
years. Therefore we must ﬁlter TX_Envm to contain data only from 2017. Making it more complicated
however, the TX_Envm data has its dates listed in a mm/dd/yyyy format and will have to be split to
into separate columns to be properly ﬁltered.
3. The TX_Health dataset has n/a values for county, symbolizing the total values for Texas. Therefore,
these n/a values must be removed.
4. Both datasets contain a lot of extraneous information that will not be used in this study, thus it will
have to be ﬁltered out. Speciﬁcs on the comparison between both datasets:
Share only 2 ID’s: County and State (with all state values being Texas)
Do not share 104 separate ID’s, with 23 diﬀerent ID’s in TX_Envm and 80 diﬀerent ID’s in
TX_Health
In total, there will be 101 ID’s that will be left out of this portion of the study.
5. The column name Average Daily PM2.5 is clumsy, and will be changed to Pollution .

However, upon a quick glance at the dataset, one would notice many diﬀerent variables without clear
deﬁnitions. Therefore, a quick discussion about the semantics of key variables within our new dataset:
: Withing the category Pollution , the unit describes the ﬁne inhalable particles, with a
diameter that are 2.5 micrometers or smaller (hence the name). It should be noted, that the World
Health Organization (WHO) sets a standard of (daily average) and the Environmental
Protection Agency (EPA) sets a standard of (daily average). It is not our place to dictate
which is correct, that distinction will be left for governmental agencies. However, it is a generally
accepted that a larger number is associated with worse pollution, and will thus be interpreted in this
manner.
Media : The Texas Commission on Environmental Quality (TCEQ) separates violations into three
distinct categories: Air, Waste, and Water. Each category contains a broad range of violations, but all
pertain to the category in which they are under. In this portion of the study, we will be investigating
violations under the category of Air .
Violation Category : The Texas Commission on Environmental Quality (TCEQ) further separates
violations based upon their Enforcement Initiation Criteria (EIC). This criteria assesses the severity of
the violation and labels the violation either as A, B, or C:
A = A regulatory violation, it is the least severe and it typically manifests itself as a failure to
report requirements (improper permits, failure to keep proper records, etc…)
B = A general violation, it is not serious by nature but poses occupational health hazards to
employees.
C = A serious violation, it is the most severe and poses serious health risks to the general
public as well as employees.

RQ 2: Salaries/Wages Per County and Respective Health
In order to begin the exploration into the relationship between the amount of money for salaries and wages
allocated to each county and the percentage of fair or poor health status, the data sets had to be cleaned
in order to be properly joined. The expenditures data set was ﬁrst ﬁltered to only include data from the year
2017, and then only the rows with a county name were selected. The data was then ﬁltered again to focus
on the salaries and wages category, and then the rows were grouped by county. A summarize function was
then used to calculate the total wages and salaries, as well as the average salaries and wages, each in
units of thousands of dollars. By grouping by county, the new data set only included one row per county,
which was the intended goal.
TX_2017_SalWage <- TX_Exp %>%
filter(`Fiscal Year` == 2017) %>% # filtering expenditure data for only 2017
filter(!is.na(County)) %>% # Removing rows with missing county name
filter(`Major Spending Category` == 'SALARIES AND WAGES') %>% # Choosing the spe
nding category
select(County, `Major Spending Category`, Amount) %>%
group_by(County) %>% # Grouping the data based on the county name
# Total and average salaries will be in units of 1000s of dollars
summarize(Total_Sal_Wages = sum(Amount)/1000,
Avg_Sal_Wages = mean(Amount)/1000)
nrow(TX_Exp)
## [1] 88707
nrow(TX_2017_SalWage)
## [1] 253

RQ 3: Total Spending and Total Violations
We will be exploring the relationship between the expenditures made by each county in the dataset
TX_Exp and the violations that occurred in the dataset TX_Envm_Violation .
It is important to ﬁrst notice that TX_Exp and TX_Envm both contain information from several diﬀerent
years. For our investigation, we are interested in information during 2017. While we can ﬁlter this straight
away with TX_Exp , we found that our TX_Envm dataset displays the dates in mm/dd/yyyy format. Thus,
we separated the column into year , month , and day columns to allow us to ﬁlter out the years.
TX_2017_Exp <- TX_Exp %>%
filter(`Fiscal Year` ==2017) # Look at only 2017 data
TX_2017_Envm <- TX_Envm %>%
## Tidying: Separating the column into 3 other columns ###
separate(`Notice of Violation Date`, # We separate the date into 3 columns
into = c("Month", "Day", "Year"), # ...month, day, and year
sep = "/",
convert = T) %>%
filter(Year == 2017) # ...then we filter 2017 data
Now, we want to calculate totals for both of the datasets before joining the two. We begin with calculating
the total amount of expenditures performed by each county. Notice that our ﬁrst county row is NA. A closer
look at this row shows that this row looks at the totals of the entirety of Texas. Thus, for our data analysis,
we would exclude this from our calculations.
TX_2017_TotalExp <- TX_2017_Exp %>%
filter(!is.na(County)) %>% # Filter out the "Texas Total" row
select(County, `Major Spending Category`, Amount) %>% # look at counties and amou
nts
group_by(County) %>% # for each county...
summarize(Total_Exp_HTh = sum(Amount)/100000, # ... Find the total expenditure
Avg_Exp_HTh = mean(Amount)/100000) # .. Find the average expenditure

3. Discussion
Through the methods in this study, three research questions were answered…
Research Question 1: What is the relationship between the amount of air violations in a given county and
the average daily “ ”?
Figure 1 displays the range of average daily “ ” for all counties in Texas, establishing that all
counties in Texas have average daily “ ” emissions that are below the regulation as set by the
Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) of . In the same vein, Figure 2 provide a clear
picture as to the relationship between the total amount of air violations and air pollution. Through
visualization of the trend line, as seen it ﬁgure 2, there is a positive correlation between the total
amount of air violations and average daily “ ”.
Research Question 2: What is the relationship between the amount of money for salaries and wages
allocated to each county and the respective percentage of fair or poor health status?
Figure 3 demonstrated that the counties in the top 10 ranks for salary and wage allocation from the
state of Texas exhibited a relationship that was similar to what was hypothesized. That is, for an
increase in the amount allocated for salaries and wages, the percentage of fair and/or poor health
status among that county’s population decreased. It is important to note that the correlation was not
strong, but a visual inspection conﬁrms that it is not 0, though for a more rigorous proof signiﬁcance
of correlation should be tested.
Figure 4 revealed that on a state-wide scale, the same pattern was not as apparent. However, it is
important to note that not many observations were apparent past $6,000,000, meaning the
regression line could be inaccurate.
Further analysis should investigate what confounding variables could be inﬂuencing health statuses.
Research Question 3: What is the relationship between the expenditures made by each county in Texas
and their respective violations?
Figure 5 displays the number of violations against the total amount of expenditure made by each
county. Each county was represented with a point and a line of best ﬁt was added into the data.
Certain outliers were removed from the ﬁnishing plot in order to focus on the cluster of data. From
the cluster, we found that there does seem to be a positive correlation between Expenditure Totals
and Violation Totals. However, it is important to emphasize that the scale of expenditures was in
Hundreds of Thousands of Dollars, meaning that such a correlation is actually weaker than what is
depicted.
Figure 7 does a similar depiction as Figure 5 with the addition of the media variable. With this, 3
more lines were constructed, demonstrating if looking at speciﬁc types of violations demonstrated a
better correlation. While Air and Waste-related violations did not show a signiﬁcant correlation, Water
Violations seemed to show a positive relationship between number of Violations and the total
expenditure made by a county. The same issues as ﬁgure 5 follow, mainly being the scale used to
construct the plot.
Figure 6 simply shows how many types of violations were classiﬁed as being labeled as either a
Water, Air, or Waste related violation. The resulting bar graph showed that Water violations were
